Digital forensic investigations generate vast quantities of logs, system events, authentication records, and user activity data that 
must be analysed to determine the sequence of actions that occurred during a security incident. While existing forensic tools are 
effective at collecting and presenting evidence, they typically rely on raw logs, tabular views, and static timelines that require 
significant expertise to interpret and can be challenging to communicate to non-technical stakeholders involved in incident response 
and decision-making. This project proposes an automated forensic investigation platform that reconstructs incident timelines from 
heterogeneous forensic artefacts, correlates related events to establish causal relationships, and transforms investigation findings 
into an interactive visual replay of incident progression. By combining automated timeline reconstruction with visual forensic 
storytelling, the platform aims to improve the understanding, communication, and analysis of complex security incidents while reducing 
the effort required to manually interpret forensic evidence. The project will further evaluate whether animated incident reconstruction 
enhances investigator comprehension and analysis efficiency when compared with traditional log-based forensic analysis approaches.
